# Web + native parity (Axis)

Axis uses **one Next.js codebase** for the website and iOS/Android apps. Capacitor loads the deployed site in a WebView — **do not build separate mobile-only portal UIs**.

## Before finishing portal / notification work

1. **Nav sections** — Update `src/lib/portals/*-sections.ts` (resident: `resident-sections.ts`), wire `render-portal-section.tsx`, and tier gating (`RESIDENT_FREE_TIER_SECTION_IDS` / `manager-access.ts`).
2. **Routes** — New top-level prefixes go in `IN_APP_PATH_PREFIXES` (`src/lib/platform/parity.ts`) so deep links and push taps work in the app.
3. **Push** — `sendPushToUser` URLs must be in-app paths; add to `REGISTERED_PUSH_DEEP_LINKS`.
4. **Uploads** — Use `useNativeCamera()` for photo flows.
5. **Safe area** — Portal shells use `portal-layout-classes.ts` and `html[data-native]` (see `globals.css`).
6. **Tests** — Run `npm run test:unit`; `platform-parity.test.ts` must pass.

## Deploy model

- **Portal UI / API** → Vercel deploy updates **web and app WebView** together.
- **Push to `production`** → also runs **iOS TestFlight**
  (`.github/workflows/ios-testflight.yml`) so the native shell stays in sync.
  Confirm that workflow after every production push (`docs/ship-gate.md`).
- **Native shell only** (plugins, icons, permissions) → `npm run cap:prod` +
  store rebuild / TestFlight.

Full guide: `docs/web-and-native-parity.md`
